Morphological terminology follows 

Broad 
et al
. (2018)

(interpreted as in 
Figs 1–3
). Diagnosis of the genus is based on 
Townes (1970)
. Measurements (in millimeters) of the morphological structures were made with a Leica M205A microscope, respectively: antenna length (
Fig. 4A
); body length (
Fig. 4A
); face width (
Fig. 4C
); frons width (
Fig. 4C
); eye height (
Fig. 4C
); basal mandible width (
Fig. 4C
); malar space (
Fig. 4C
); ocellus diameter (
Fig. 4D
); distance between posterior ocelli (
Fig. 4D
); shortest distance between anterior and posterior ocelli (
Fig. 4D
); shortest distance between posterior ocellus and compound eye (
Fig. 4D
); fore and hind wing length (
Fig. 4A
); length and width of tergites 1 
–
3 (
Fig. 4B
); and ovipositor length (
Fig. 4A
).

Digital images were taken with a Leica M205A stereo microscope coupled with a Leica DMC4500 camera and Leica Application Suite 
V
4.10.0 Interactive Measurements & Montage and superimposed using Helicon Focus software, version 7.0 Pro. The mesopleuron images (lateral view) were taken with a TESCAN® Model VEGA3 Scanning Electron Microscope (SEM) without metallization pretreatment. Distribution maps of the species were made using SimpleMappr software (
Shorthouse 2010
) with georeferencing data taken from specimen labels and data available in the literature (
