Diagnosis.

Chirotica mariua


sp. nov.

can be distinguished from all other Neotropical 

Chirotica
species

by the combination of the following characters: 
(1)
pronotum with a posterolateral crest (
Fig. 25A
); 
(2)
pronotal collar whitish-yellow (
Fig. 25A
); 
(3)
mesopleuron on the posterior part without punctuation and/or rugae; 
(4)
tergite 3 slightly granulated with sparse punctuation (
Fig. 25E
); 
(5)
lower valve of ovipositor with small proximal teeth scattered at apex (
Fig. 25F
).

